post_text:
We have an important update regarding learning options for students for the first semester of the 2020-2021 school year.

Schools will continue to accommodate parent requests made through 12:00 p.m. on September 18th for students to move to digital learning or face-to-face learning. After that day and time, no changes will be made through the end of the first semester. This is necessary so that schools can establish stability in the master schedule to ensure that students are receiving consistent high-quality instruction and that parents can receive feedback in a timely manner on their student‚Äôs progress and grades.

Parent requests for changes to digital learning or face-to-face learning for the second semester will be able to be made to your child‚Äôs school during the week of November 30 ‚Äì December 4. #SDOCStartSmart

Every student in kindergarten through tenth grade needs to take the NWEA Beginning of Year Math Baseline test. Math teachers have been guiding our digital learning students on the process this week.

If your child hasn‚Äôt taken the test, please help them test as soon as possible.

This test can be accessed at: https://test.mapnwea.org/

You will need a session name and session password that was provided by your child's teacher. Please contact them if you do not have it. *Protip: Turn of your pop-up blocker on your browser!

If you need technical help with the test, you can find support by either calling your child‚Äôs school, or by calling our help line at: 407-870-4037. Lines open at 7:00 a.m. on Tuesday.

We currently have 37,801 overdue books across the district from last school year. Many of these missing books are because of closing schools in March due to COVID-19.

If we were to replace each of those books at an average of $20 per book, that would total $756,020.

Help us recover these lost books by returning your overdue school library books to your school. The school media center with the most returned books will win a media center prize pack! #SDOCGoodtoGreat

It is the goal of the Osceola County School District to be completely transparent in reporting COVID-19 incidents so that all of its stakeholders feel informed about the number of positive cases in its schools. Today, we have launched a new webpage for parents and the community to check to see the number of COVID-19 incidents in our schools each week.

Please visit: www.osceolaschools.net/COVID-19Incidents

Every Monday, we will post the total number of students and school personnel by school who have notified the district of positive COVID-19 test results for the week prior, as well as the number of students and school personnel who have been told to quarantine beginning that week. #SDOCStartSmart

post_text:
This just in!

Governor DeSantis issued Executive Order 20-212 that extends the deadline for students graduating in the 2019-20 school year to earn the minimum qualifying SAT or ACT score to earn a Bright Futures scholarship until December 1, 2020.

This will positively impact thousands of students statewide and in our own district who either need to earn a qualifying score or wanted to take either the SAT or ACT again to earn a higher score.

Estimates after the closure of school campuses in Spring 2020 suggested approximately 32,000 seniors had, excluding their SAT or ACT test score, otherwise met all other Bright Futures requirements. Historical trends show that if given another opportunity to take the SAT or ACT, approximately one-quarter (8,000) of those students would qualify for either a 75% or 100% Bright Futures scholarship. #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text:
The Osceola School District requires face masks on all campuses across the district, for students and staff. We've updated our face mask requirements as we continue to learn more about the most effective procedures for keeping everyone healthy.

Clear plastic shields are not adequate protection when used alone. A face mask needs to be worn when wearing a face shield.

In addition, neck gaiters need to be double-lined in order to provide adequate protection. Single lined neck gaiters will no longer be considered acceptable as a face covering.

We appreciate your continued support as we work together for a successful school year for all. #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text: Did you know? Mobile Crisis Services are available to anyone ages 0 - 24 located in Orange, Osceola, or Seminole County at the time of crisis. Master level and licensed therapists will respond to homes, schools, or anywhere in the tri-county community, within 60 minutes to provide immediate on-site crisis stabilization. Crisis therapists also connect families to the services and supports they need for long-term recovery.

The COVID-19 pandemic has impacted multiple staff members at Harmony Middle School during this past week. Out of an abundance of caution, the Osceola School District has decided to move all teachers and students at Harmony Middle School to digital learning starting Monday, August 31, for the next two weeks. Students and staff will return for face-to-face learning on Monday, September 14. This does not impact those students who have already been engaged in digital learning at Harmony Middle School.

Click below for information on digital devices, curbside meal pick up, and COVID-19 testing.

post_text: In our final video in our series related to back-to-school during the COVID-19 pandemic, we discuss what response to the virus will look like. Our back-to-school protocols rely heavily on face coverings for students and staff, daily self-screenings for COVID-19 symptoms, social distancing, and hand washing and sanitizing, but we understand there may come a time when someone tests positive for COVID-19. Here's how we'll respond. #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text: Of all the complex decisions education leaders face as they plan to reopen schools for the 2020-2021 academic year, one of the toughest might be the most basic: how to get students to the buildings in the first place. While the number of students who ride the bus will be smaller, as some students are learning digitally, the district still has to think through logistics to keep students, bus drivers, and bus attendants safe and healthy to and from school. Take a peek at what our buses will look like when we start back to school on August 24. #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text:
The Osceola School District has a plan in place for what school meal service will look like when we flip the calendar to another academic year on August 24th.

Feeding children is what we do; and COVID-19 has just meant that we have to make some adjustments to keep our students and staff healthy and safe. One thing we know for sure: School meals will become increasingly integral to child nutrition as families continue to grapple with pandemic-related unemployment and financial hardships.

Information on Curbside Meals for Digital Learning students will be posted later today, stay tuned! #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

With all of the uncertainty that 2020 has brought us, we know for certain that this upcoming academic year will be unlike any we've experienced before. Despite the challenges we have already faced this year, our educators and employees rose up and delivered for our students so that learning never stopped in the Osceola School District.

Today is the first day back for the 2020-2021 school year for our teachers and many staff and we welcome everyone with this message, dedicated to the true strength of our district: our dedicated and amazing employees! #SDOCGoodtoGreat #SDOCStartSmart #LearningNeverStopsinSDOC

post_text:
Schools are busily working on finalizing student master schedules and teacher assignments for the 2020-2021 school year. Student schedules will be available in FOCUS starting Monday, August 17, in preparation for the first day of school on Monday, August 24.

As of right now, your child‚Äôs schedule will be built based on your most recent selection for how they will return to school this year. If you never made a selection, your child will be enrolled in face-to-face instruction.

If you need to change your selection, you can contact your child‚Äôs school starting Monday, September 14, to begin the process. The change will take at least a week to be made. Schools are unable to make any further changes at this time in order to complete student schedules in time for them to be ready on August 17. #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text:
We have a #protip that may be especially helpful for parents of students who are moving to a new school this year (ie. former fifth graders moving on to sixth grade) and want to start receiving communication from the new school.

You can opt-in to your child's new school by finding their Remind code, or links to their social media channels, on our website at https://www.osceolaschools.net/connectwithus

While parents will be auto-enrolled in their child's new classes via Remind once class lists and schedules have been created, this is a great option until that takes place.

If you are receiving messages from a school and you'd like to opt-out, just follow the directions found in the Remind Help Center, here: https://help.remind.com/hc/en-us/articles/202540968?

The Osceola School Board approved an update to the Ready. Set. Start Smart! School Reopening Plan for the 2020-2021 school year at last night's Board Meeting.

In accordance with revised CDC guidelines that were issued last Friday for school reopening, we will now require students to wear face coverings at all times while in classrooms.

We appreciate your support in preparing for a successful return to school in August and your patience when changes like these must occur. This pandemic is ever-changing and we must adapt and update our plans when necessary. #SDOCStartSmart

Please disregard the athletics update that was sent out at the end of last week (found below). Based on the vote by the Florida High School Athletic Association's Board of Directors on July 23, the start date of all fall sports will now be postponed until at least August 24.

FHSAA staff w ill be working to come up with alternate plans for the 2020-2021 school year, and will present such plan(s) to their Board for approval at a Board of Directors Meeting to be held on August 17.

After those plans are approved, the Osceola School District will evaluate how high school athletics will proceed. Until that time, athletic conditioning may continue with a maximum of three days a week.

Osceola County School District
June 25 at 6:42 PM ¬∑

In consultation with our School Board Counsel and per the Chairman‚Äôs direction, due to the recent spike in COVID-19 cases, the Board Workshop and Board Meeting scheduled for Tuesday, June 30, will be held virtually.

You can tune in live to the Board Workshop at 4:00 p.m. at https://bit.ly/VBW0630.

You can tune in live to the Special School Board Meeting about Back-to-School/Back-to-Learning Plans at 5:30 p.m. at https://bit.ly/VBM0630.

3. Email a 3-minute video comment, including name and address for the record, to the public comment email no later than noon on Monday, June 29.

Emails and text messages will be included in the published minutes of the meeting.

The Osceola School District collects student laptops, and hot spots, at the end of the school year so devices may be prepped before the next school year.

Families should return student devices as indicated on the signed borrower‚Äôs form. Thank you for your attention and cooperation. #SDOCGoodtoGreat #LearningNeverStopsinSDCOC

post_text: We are appreciative and in support of the guidance given today by Governor DeSantis and Education Commissioner Corcoran on the reopening of our schools in August. This important information will be used as a framework as we draft our Back-to-School and Back-to-Learning plans to ensure students return to safe classrooms. We will continue to make closing any achievement gaps students may have experienced due to school closures a priority, with a strong focus on literacy and early learning. Recommendations for our Back-to-School plan will be presented to the Osceola School Board on June 30, 2020. Communication to parents, teachers/staff, and the community will begin immediately upon approval so plans can be made for a successful start of school. #LearningNeverStopsinSDOC #SDOCGoodtoGreat #SDOCStartSmart

post_text:
The Osceola School District is hard at work to determine what learning will look like in the fall. Superintendent Dr. Debra Pace has created a Back-To-School Task Force that is looking into how to best keep students and staff safe when school resumes on August 10, 2020.

The Task Force, which is made up of school and community stakeholders including medical professionals specializing in infectious diseases, parents, teachers, and school and district administrators, will make recommendations to Superintendent Pace, who will then present a plan to the Osceola County School Board for final approval.

An important part of the planning process for next school year is hearing from Osceola educators. Input from teachers is being collected through this short survey as to what would be your preferred approach to educating the students assigned to you at the start of next school year. The survey can be found at osceolaschools.net/teachersurvey, The deadline for the survey is June 15, 2020. #SDOCGoodtoGreat #SDOCStartSmart

The Osceola School District is hard at work to determine what learning will look like in the fall for its 69,000 students. Superintendent Dr. Debra Pace has created a Back-To-School Task Force that is looking into how to best keep students and staff safe when school resumes on August 10, 2020.

The Task Force, which is made up of school and community stakeholders including medical professionals specializing in infectious diseases, parents, teachers, and school and district administrators, will make recommendations to Superintendent Pace, who will then present a plan to the Osceola County School Board for final approval.

Be assured that the safety of students and staff will always be at the forefront of all decisions that are made. Solid plans for multiple scenarios will be developed based on science, data, and guidance in alignment with the Florida Department of Education and local and state public health departments. #SDOCStartSmart #SDOCGoodtoGreat

The Osceola School District will not be mass-printing report cards. Instead, parents and students can view and print them from both the parent portal and student portal in FOCUS. Report cards for elementary students will be available online starting June 5, and report cards for middle and high school students will be available online on June 12.

Parents can visit www.osceolaschools.net/reportcardinfo for specific directions to view and print the report cards according to their child‚Äôs grade level. No report cards will be picked up since they all will be available via the Focus portal. If necessary, parents may call the school and request a printed copy to be mailed.

shared_text:
Terry Castillo, Osceola County School Board Member - District 1
May 26 at 1:12 PM ¬∑

The 4th edition (and the first bilingual edition ever) of Coming to America is now out! Included in this book are 17 simple, yet powerful, stories written in English and Spanish from our current ESOL population at Osceola High. There are also 7 stories from ex-ESOL students who graduated in previous years from OHS (24 stories in all, 246 pages).

According to recent research (The English Journal), the Coming to America club at OHS is the only high school club in the United States of America which has published four books in a series... WOW!

These photos include 2020 OHS seniors, Crismeyling Sanchez, Gelmary Matheus, and the Club President, Lilliana Abou-Nasser. #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text:
Okay, Osceola County!

It's time to update your Facebook Frames to show your support for our Osceola School District Seniors! We have one for EVERY single public high school (so students can grab their own if they are on Facebook*), one for parents of a graduating senior, and then this one for the community to show their love!

Just search "SDOC Seniors" when adding a new frame to your profile pic (try to remove any old frames too, you can do this by saying "Change Picture" when you're placing your new frame and it will let you pick a new picture of yourself). #SDOCGoodtoGreat #SDOCSeniors2020

*If they aren't on Facebook but want the frame for Instagram, Twitter, or any other social media platform they may be using, have them email heather.kahoun@osceolaschools.net and she can provide it to them.

post_text:
Due to COVID-19 and social distancing recommendations, we continue to run Virtual School Board Meetings and Workshops until further notice. Our next will take place Tuesday, May 19, 2020.

If you'd like to tune in live during the workshop, join us at https://bit.ly/VBW0519 at 3:00 p.m.

The Virtual School Board Meeting will start at 5:30 p.m. and you can tune in live during the meeting at https://bit.ly/VBM0519.

** We have an update on how you can address the School Board for Public Comment during the meeting **

If you wish to address the School Board, you may do so by submitted Public Comment in one of three ways:

1. Email: PublicComments@osceolaschools.net no later than one hour prior to the scheduled Board meeting; or

2. Send a text message to (407) 288-7330 no later than one hour prior to the scheduled Board meeting; or

3. Email a 3-minute video comment, including name and address for the record, to the public comment email no later than noon on Monday, May 18.

Emails and text messages will be included in the published minutes of the meeting. #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text:
Have you sent your teacher a certificate of appreciation yet today? It‚Äôs so easy to do! Just...

1) Visit www.osceolaschools.net/teacher_certificate and click on the picture of the certificate to download it.

2) Fill the certificate out and save it to your computer.

3) Open up ClassLink and navigate to Office365 and your Outlook email.

4) Email it to your teacher! If you‚Äôve never emailed your teacher before, visit your school‚Äôs website to find out what his/her email address is. Most email addresses are firstname.lastname@osceolaschools.net

You will be sure to put a smile on your teacher‚Äôs face with this last Teacher Appreciation Week surprise! #weloveSDOCteachers #SDOCGoodtoGreat #TeacherAppreciationWeek

Your last mission during Teacher Appreciation Week... fill your teacher's inbox! You can find the fillable certificate at www.osceolaschools.net/teacher_certificate.

Download, fill it out, save it, and send it to your teacher(s) to let them know how much you appreciate them.

If you don't know your teacher's email address, visit your school's website and find the staff directory to locate it. Most email addresses are firstname.lastname@osceolaschools.net though!

Okay, let's go! #weloveSDOCteachers #SDOCGoodtoGreat #TeacherAppreciationWeek

post_text:
To ensure that students have nutritious meals while away from school, the district's School Nutrition Services Department will provide FREE breakfast and lunch to children 18 years and under during the extended school closure.

We have added one additional student feeding site (Highlands Elementary) and changed a site from Michigan Avenue Elementary to St. Cloud High (starting on 5/4).

In addition to this, beginning May 4, meals will be available for pick-up four days a week - Monday through Thursday. The meal sites will not be distributing food on Fridays. Food for Fridays will be provided in the Thursday meal pick-up. Click the link below for more details and to see a list of all the feeding sites.

To increase access to COVID-19 testing, Florida Department of Health (DOH)-Osceola will offer testing events at different locations throughout the county.

The first event is scheduled at St. Cloud High School Friday, May 1, and Monday, May 4 from 9:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.

Testing is available for anyone who is experiencing COVID-19 symptoms (fever, cough, shortness of breath). Those meeting criteria should call 407-343-2000 to schedule an appointment. Future events will be announced as scheduled.

Are you a high school student still in need of a laptop to engage in digital learning?

Parents of high school students who are still in need of a laptop for digital learning are asked to please contact their school by 2:00 p.m. tomorrow, Friday, April 3, to reserve a computer. Parents may reserve one device for each high school student in their home.

If you are currently on a waitlist already at your school for a loaner laptop, there is no need to contact the school again.

The schools will notify parents who made reservations about the day and time for computer pickup next week. If the district has laptops remaining after the high school reservations are filled, we will open up an additional device distribution process for middle school students next. #LearningNeverStopsinSDOC

Please be aware that Microsoft is experiencing world-wide performance issues with the Teams platform, and we have been assured that Microsoft is working as quickly as possible to resolve these performance challenges.

For those signing into the Teams platform for the first time, there could be an additional wait time of up to 24 hours to be provisioned. We will send out additional notifications as these issues are resolved.

We appreciate your patience during this time, and please be flexible and patient with your students as we work through these challenges in the coming days. Teachers will be flexible with assignment deadlines this first week as we all adjust to this new way of learning together.

We have an important update on our free meals for students during school closures!

Three new student feeding sites have been added and we are extending the feeding time each day beginning on Monday, March 30, 2020.

In addition, the Osceola School District has been approved to take advantage of a state waiver that allows parents to pick up food for children without the child being present, as long as parents can produce viable identification for the children.

Finally, Lynx will begin offering complimentary rides on their routes for parents and students to get to the stops as close as possible to the feeding sites. Full details on everything here: https://osceolaschools.net/coronavirus_information

post_text:
An important COVID-19 and digital learning update from the Osceola School District as of March 20, 2020:

Thank you for your continued support and patience during this rapidly changing time; with COVID-19, the situation has been changing day by day, hour by hour. We are committed to providing parents and students with the latest information as it unfolds during the school closure period.

The Osceola School District is preparing to transition to student digital learning starting the week of March 30. We want to make this change as easy as possible. All resources for students and families will be available through the ClassLink platform, which the students are familiar with using, on the district website at www.osceolaschools.net and can be accessed using any digital device (such as a smartphone, laptop, desktop computer, or tablet).

For all details in regards to our plan for moving instruction online, please visit our district website at www.osceolaschools.net/coronavirus_information

post_text:
COVID-19 Update as of March 10: All Central Florida school superintendents continue to carefully monitor the COVID-19 situation. Following a call with the Florida Commissioner of Education this morning and based on his strong recommendations, all student fieldtrips involving air travel will be suspended immediately through the end of the current school year. District and school staff members will work with parents and travel companies on appropriate cancellation arrangements.

While we have been advised by experts that the risk to young people remains low, we encourage everyone to continue to follow the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) guidelines and to follow healthy habits. Hand washing with soap and water remains the best prevention.

post_text: Today our friends at the Education Foundation of Osceola County and Universal Orlando Foundation launched the Pencil Boy Express at Westside K-8! This program is an expansion of A Gift For Teaching and will provide school supplies to all of our Osceola School District schools located 15 miles or more from our A Gift For Teaching store. No longer will these schools go without because teachers struggle to visit our free store because of geographical challenges. Thank you to all who made this program a reality! #SDOCGoodtoGreat

post_text: The 2020 Census is coming and we're counting on you to count us all in! This once-a-decade population count serves as the basis for distributing federal assistance to school and educational institutions, including Title I aid, the National School Lunch Program, and special education grants to states. Mark your calendars now for April 1, 2020, and visit www.census.gov to learn more! #2020Census

post_text: An important message for the parents of Denn John Middle: A non-specific threat has been detected on social media potentially in reference to Denn John Middle School. The Kissimmee Police Department is actively investigating the situation, and school leadership will keep parents, students, and staff informed as the situation progresses via social media and Remind. At this time, school will operate as usual tomorrow, Thursday, and additional law enforcement and district security will be present as necessary.
